At the end of the course of studies, students are expected to acquire the ability to
1. understand basic structural programming constructs in building a working software;
2. apply computer programming to solve engineering problems;
3. model a system on a computer to meet specifications and performance goals.

Upon successful completion of this course, students will be able to:

1. have a basic understanding of the concept and principles of AI;
2. have a basic understanding of machine learning principles;
3. learn the use of common generative AI tools to assist their learning;
4. understand the ethics of using AI responsibly.

This course is built around the fundamental understanding of basic principles, techniques, and applications of AI. The cornerstone of this course involves evaluation of AI systems in our daily lives and exploring potential solutions with AI and machine learning technologies. Upon successful completion of the course, students shall be able to achieve the following outcomes:

1. explain the basic concepts and major elements of today's AI technology;
2. understand and use the basic terminology of AI;
3. describe the basic types of tasks that an AI system can accomplish;
4. explain the operation of major applications of AI;
5. suggest possible new use cases of AI;
6. explain the role of data in AI;
7. describe the workflow for AI application development.

Upon successful completion of the course, students will be able to:
1. explain the meanings of signals and systems from engineering perspectives and with connection to real-world applications;
2. demonstrate how signals and systems can be represented by mathematical expressions;
3. explain the concepts of frequency and frequency spectrum;
4. describe and explain the types and properties of systems, with an emphasis on linear time-invariant systems;
5. use Laplace transform or z-transform to represent a linear system;
6. analyze and explain the behavior of a linear system;
7. explain the sampling theorem and its physical implications.

By the end of this course, students should beable to
- understand Bayesian decision theory;
- describe some pattern recognition algorithms;
- understand how different pattern recognitionalgorithms work and the conditions for them to work;
- understand the strength and limitations ofdifferent pattern recognition algorithms;
- understand the major challenges in patternrecognition;
- implement some algorithms learned from thecourse using matlab and know how to use existingtoolboxes;
- apply pattern recognition algorithms to solvesome practical problems.

