courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) grasp the fundamentals of kinematics, dynamics, and control system development for robotic system;
(2) gain exposure to the latest developments in robotics;
(3) gain exposure to robotic algorithm implementation;
(4) develop your intuition on robot modeling and analysis through developing simulation and robot controller implementation.

Upon completion of the course, students should have achieved the following outcomes:
(1) gain understanding with photolithography, isotropic and anisotropic wet etching, dry etching, physical and chemical vapor deposition, electroplating, MEMS release etching, stiction, and MEMS device testing;
(2) articulate state-of-the-art MEMS technologies in observing, manipulation and measuring molecules, cells and tissues.

The students who take this course shall be able to
1. Describe the basic principles of biomechanics and apply them to understand the biological systems at the cell, tissue, organ and whole person levels;
2. Engineer solutions to biomechanically augment the functions of patients in clinical medicine;
3. Describe the properties of major categories of biomaterials and explain the rationale for their uses in medicine;
4. Understand the processing technology of biomaterials; and
5. Critically review the state-of-the-art researches in biomechanics and biomaterials.

